{"cursor":"11583","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Secondary Causation' âCausality Primary and Secondaryâ, Mariano Artigas,\nEncyclopedia of Science and Religion, Â©2003 Gale Cengage; online at http://www.enotes.com/causality-primary-secondary-reference/causality-primary-\nsecondary âKantâs Theory of Divine and Secondary Causationâ , Des\nHogan, University of California at San Diego; online at http://philosophy.ucsd.edu/_files/facultysites/watkins-\nconference/hogan.pdf; âCausation as a Secondary Qualityâ, Peter\nMenzies and Huw Price, Brit. J. Phil. Sci., 44 (1993), 187-203. is the\nphilosophical proposition that all material and corporeal objects, having been\ncreated by God with their own intrinsic potentialities, are subsequently\nempowered to evolve independently in accordance with natural law. Traditional\nChristians would slightly modify this injunction to allow for the occasional\nmiracle as well as the exercise of free will. Deists who deny any divine\ninterference past the creation event would only accept free will exceptions.\nThat the physical universe is consequentially well-ordered, consistent, and\nknowable subject to human observation and reason, was a primary theme of\nScholasticism and further molded into the philosophy of the Western Tradition by\nAugustine and later by Aquinas.\n\nSecondary causation has been suggested as a necessary precursor for scientific\ninquiry into an established order of natural laws which are not entirely\npredicated on the changeable whims of a supernatural Being. Huff, Toby E.\nThe Rise of Early Modem Science: Islam, China and the West, Cambridge University\nPress, (2003). Nor does this create a conflict between science and\nreligion for, given a Creator, it is not inconsistent with the paradigm of a\nclockwork universe. It does however remove logical contradictions concerning the\nunfettered expression of manâs free will which would otherwise require not just\nGodâs acquiescence but rather His direct intervention to implement.\n","linknr":139,"url":"Secondary_Causation","recorded":1374783770,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Secondary_causation&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Secondary_causation&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Secondary_causation","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Secondary_Causation&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","#cite_note-1","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","/wiki/Scholasticism","/wiki/Augustine","/wiki/Aquinas","#cite_note-4","/wiki/Clockwork_universe","#Opposing_Philosophies_of_Volunteerism_and_Occasionalism_against_Secondary_Causation","#Opposing_Philosophy_of_.E2.80.9DDual_Truth.E2.80.9D_against_Secondary_Causation","#Development_of_Philosophy_in_Support_of_Secondary_Causation","#References","/w/index.php?title=Secondary_causation&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Occasionalism","/wiki/Al-Ash%27ari","/wiki/Al-Ghazali","#cite_note-5","#cite_note-6","#cite_note-7","#cite_note-8","/wiki/Al-Mutawakkil","/wiki/Albert_Magnus","/wiki/Thomas_Aquinas","/wiki/Moses_Maimonides","/wiki/Luis_de_Molina","/wiki/Francisco_Su%C3%A1rez","/wiki/Renaissance","#cite_note-9","#cite_note-10","/wiki/Al-Ash%27ari","/wiki/Fourth_Council_of_the_Lateran","/wiki/Ex_nihilo","/w/index.php?title=Secondary_causati